To achieve 100% code coverage for the `CsvToJsonConverterException` class, you need to test the constructor to ensure it appropriately sets the message. Since this is a simple extension of `RuntimeException`, the primary focus is on verifying that the exception is constructed correctly. Below is an example of how you might write a JUnit 5 test case to achieve this in Java:

```java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;

class CsvToJsonConverterExceptionTest {

    @Test
    void testExceptionMessage() {
        // Arrange
        String message = "This is a test message";

        // Act
        CsvToJsonConverterException exception = new CsvToJsonConverterException(message);

        // Assert
        assertNotNull(exception);
        assertEquals(message, exception.getMessage());
    }
}
```

This single test case should provide 100% code coverage for the `CsvToJsonConverterException` class as it verifies that the message provided to the constructor is correctly set and can be retrieved via the `getMessage()` method of the `RuntimeException` class.